1. Why do we convert continuous values into categories?
To make data easier to understand and analyze. Instead of many numbers, we group them into simple labels like Gold, Silver, and Bronze.

2. What is the difference between business segmentation and technical bucketing?

Business segmentation → based on business rules (e.g., spend > 100 = Gold)
Technical bucketing → based on data or algorithms (e.g., quantiles, bucketizer)

3. When would fixed thresholds fail?
They fail when data distribution changes. For example, if most customers spend very high or very low, the categories become unbalanced.

4. How does quantile-based segmentation differ from fixed rules?

Fixed rules → use predefined values
Quantile-based → divides data into equal-sized groups based on distribution

5. Which method would you use in real-world projects?

Use conditional logic when business rules are fixed
Use quantile or ranking when you want balanced, data-driven segmentation
